column168: On May 1, 2019 at 1103 EST, ERTS received a call from XPO Logistics terminal XAY regarding a hazardous cargo release. The caller reported that (1) 55-gallon fiberboard drum of UN2556, Nitrocellulose with alcohol, 4.1, PGII "Walsroder" arrived punctured inside of the trailer. The caller stated that it "appeared that someone at the domicile terminal in Columbus, OH punctured the drum with a forklift then plastic wrapped the damaged drum and shipped it on. The caller stated that there was less than 1 pound of powder on the trailer floor and the other released product was contained in the plastic wrap. At 1135 EST, ERTS dispatched Hepaco to respond. At 1258 EST, Hepaco arrived onsite and confirmed that approximately 0.5 cup of product had released to the trailer floor. The contractor over packed the damaged drum into (1) 85-gallon metal drum and placed the released material inside as well. The waste drum was staged on site at the terminal in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: The eight piece shipment was sent as overpacks. One overpack had come open during sort operations. Based on my 32 years of DG experience I knew that many times the inner containers inside an overpack do not have the required markings that are required under the auspices of an overpack. Upon removing one of the 36 inner boxes I found that the only marking the package displayed was a ground Limited Quantity mark, not an Excepted Quantity mark. I opened the inner box to reveal one plastic barrier bag containing two opaque empty plastic bottles and one brown glass bottle with 11.7 grams of UN2585. The shipper chose to offer as an overpack when in fact the entire contents of each outer box did not exceed the 1 kg maximum allowable as a PG III Excepted Quantity. The shipment was held pending an FAA inspection. The FAA was notified electronically.

column168: XPO Logistics reported to ERTS that (1) 5 gallon metal drum was punctured when the wood from a damaged pallet impacted it, causing the hazardous material Perasan A (UN 3098) to be released onto the dock floor.  The contractor (Lone Star Hazmat) were dispatched due to the size of the spill released (40 gallons) and the type of material.  The contractor cleaned the spill area and placed the damaged drum and remaining product into (1) 110 gallon poly drum.   They placed the waste and spent absorbents into (2) 55 gallon poly drums.  Note:  The contractors neutralized the waste debris inside the (2) 55 gallon drums according to the SDS. This caused a reactor to release hot fumes up to 190 degrees.  They had to allow the process to complete and placed the 2 drums at the back of the terminal with 2 loosely fitting lids.  They advised that they would return on Monday - May 6, 2019 to overpack the (2) 5 gallon drums and place the proper lids on the 2 waste drums.

column168: At approximately 0500 hours on Sunday, May 5, 2019 PTRA train crews observed product leaking from TILX 101029 on track 100 in the PTRA Manchester Yard.  The Trainmaster was notified and Slick Response was called out to respond to the event.  Slick arrived on scene at 0600 hours and found two loose flange bolts on the 2" vent valve and two loose bolts on the flange of the fill hole.  Slick personnel were able to tighten the bolts sufficiently to stop the flow of product. Acid on the car and on the ground were neutralized and remediated. Arrangements were made with ECO Services to spot the car immediately so they could off load the product and inspect the car further. The car was moved under one quarter mile to the consignee for unloading and inspection. ECO unloaded the rail car and had Trinity Rail Car pressure test the car, no leaks were observed. The car was released back into service on May 7, 2019. Rick Ferguson with Shell Chemical Co. was notified of the leak at 0513 hours on Sunday, May 5 and coordinated the response and remediation with PTRA.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Inner Packaging
column168: Arkema classified and packaged the material.  Each inner poly container was reported to contain a  solution of 4 gallons of mineral spirits and 1 gallon of organic peroxide.  Arkema stated that there was  approximately 0.97% organic peroxide in each container.  The poly containers were then packaged in 5 gallon fiber boxes and taped shut for shipment.  The containers were then transported to Veolia's ten day intransit facility located in Philadelphia, PA.  Upon unloading the truck it was found that a reaction had occurred causing some of the inner containers to rupture and some to bulge.  The ruptured  containers caused the taped lids of the outer fiber containers to come off resulting in approximately 1.5 gallons of liquid to be spilled on the floor of the trailer.  All containers in the trailer were properly  segregated and loaded onto pallets which prevented the spilled material to contaminate any other  packagings.  The spill was cleaned up in house by the Veolia Reactives Manager and dock supervisor. The leaking containers were repacked into 55 gallon lined poly drums to be shipped for disposal.
column169: Veolia's customer, Arkema was notified of the incident and recommended further training to prevent a reoccurrence.

column168: The shipment was discovered leaking in the sort. Upon opening the box we found a second box. We opened the inner box to find two eight liter plastic bottles. Each plastic bottle had a screw on cap. The root cause of the spill was an absence of any Positive Closure in violation of 49CFR 173.27(d). One of the screw on caps had become loose and allowed the spill to occur. The two bottles in the inner box were designed for the plain non-UN Specification box. The shipper used kraft paper for the dunnage between the two boxes. Based on the aforementioned violations the shipment was held pending an FAA inspection. The FAA was notified electronically.

column168: On May 1, 2019, at 0119 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics Terminal XTM of a cargo release.  It was reported that, for unknown reasons, approximately 7 ounces of CB F-159M (Adhesives, flammable, UN1133) onto the trailer and dock floor.  There was adequate ventilation for terminal personnel to clean up the release with absorbents and the appropriate PPE. Absorbents, released material and other debris were placed into (1) 30-gallon metal drum and staged at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

On May 1, 2019, 0300, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal NNA about a cargo release. It was reported that, approximately 30 gallons of Cumar R-16A resin (Flammable liquid, n.o.s., UN1993) was released from (1) 250-gallon metal tote onto the trailer floor.  It was determined that the release was due to there being no gasket on the top of the container.  The release was cleaned up with absorbents and the appropriate PPE. The spent absorbents and other debris were placed into (2) 55-gallon metal drums and staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On May 09, 2019 at 2300 EST, XPO Logistics terminal NAT experienced an approximate 3-quart UN2734 "Methoxy Proplyamine" release to trailer 3177232 and dock floor. The release was a result of puncture to container due to improper loading causing freight to fall. After reviewing SDS it was determined a contractor would be dispatched due to the PPE requirements. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed material was reacting with air, the trailer was moved away from dock and door was opened for ventilation. The release has impacted approximately 20' x 6' area under trailer during clean up process. Absorbents were utilized on released material and recovered. The cargo from trailer was off-loaded, citric acid was utilized to neutralize, solidify and was swept into drums. The damaged drum was containerized into one (1) 95-gallon poly overpack drum along with absorbent material (liquid), the spent absorbents were containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted absorbent was placed into one (1) 35-gallon poly drum and two (2) 5-gallon poly drums. Impacted PPE and debris were containerized into (1) 55-gallon poly drum. All waste was staged in terminal OS&D area for the terminal to manage proper disposal.

17:30  Slick Response received a call from Kirk Higbie with PTRA stating that they had a rail car, GATX 215064  on East Blvd in Pasadena that was called in as pouring product from the top of the car and asked that Slick personnel inspect the car and make any needed repairs, and clean car if needed. The product in the car is Methanol.  Upon arriving on location, Slick personnel climbed to the top of the car and opened the dome lid where the we found the liquid line valve in the open position, and the plug on the valve was only hand tight, allowing the product to escape. Slick personnel closed the valve, and placed Teflon tape on the plug and threaded the plug down. At this point, Slick personnel contacted Kirk and informed him of what was found, and the car was released. Slick personnel were released from service at this time.  PTRA notified Karl Kuhn, Operations VP, with ITC at the time of the incident.  Karl requested that the PTRA use their ER contractor to respond to the incident. ITC is investigating the cause of the open valve and loose plug

column168: Upon conducting an inspection of GATX 80613 it was observed that the vacuum relief device was defective and allowing vapor pressure to release from inside the tank car.  The tank car was off gassed and the vacuum relief device removed and replaced with a stainless steel plug so the car could travel under an OTMA3 for repair. It was determined that the possible cause was residue rust build up was trapped between the seal closure which did not allow the valve to seat correctly.
column169: (NAR cause code: 1122 What Failed: Vaccum Relief Valve, actuating Where Failed: Valve seat Why Failed: Valve stuck open)

column168: Inspection of car found car leaking vapor gas product from threads at Sample Port into Bolted Pressure Plate. Removed Sample Port from Bolted Pressure Plate and applied thread tape to threads. Reinstalled Sample Port into Bolted Pressure Plate. Car was resealed and OTMA applied for recertification.
column169: Proper inspection before loading, unloading, and before releasing for shipment. (NAR: 662)

column168: PRELOADER FOUND A LEAKING HAZ MAT PACKAGE IN HIS AREA, AND DID NOT TOUCH, LEFT THE AREA, NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR AND STOPPED THE PROGRESS. AS A DESIGNATED RESPONDER, I APPROACHED THE PACKAGE WITH MY PPE AND DECISION TREE. THE DECISION TREE LEAD ME TO THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET AND I FOLLOWED ALL ACTION STEPS FOR PROPER CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 4 1LITER BOTTLES WITH THE CAPS TAPED CLOSED. THE TAPE DID NOT SUCCESSFULLY KEEP THE LIDS CLOSED RESULTING IN SPILLAGE IN AND AROUND THE CARDBOARD CONTAINER.
column169: TIGHTEN CAPS WITH A WRENCH AND TAPE MULTIPLE TIMES. POSSIBLY BAG EACH BOTTLE AND GOOSENECK THE BAGS TO CONTAIN ANY SPILLAGE.

column168: RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED OF A HAZMAT PKG WITH A STRONG ODOR. PKG TRANSPORTED TO PROCESSING AREA. INSPECTION REVEALED NO PHYSICAL DAMAGED BUT 2 CAPS LEAKED WHEN BOTTLES WERE UPSIDE DOWN. ONE OTHER CAP WAS ALSO LOOSE. SHIPPER IS EXCEPTION TO SALVAGE DRUM PROCEDURES.
column169: CAPS SHOULD BE TIGHTENED PRIOR TO SHIPPING AND SECURED TO PREVENT CAP LOOSENING/BACKING OFF.

column168: On May 15, 2019 at 11:00 EST, XPO Logistics UDV terminal experienced an approximate 30-ounce UN1263, Paint Related Material (flammable), 3, PGII release. column168: On May 17, 2019 at 20:35, XPO Logistics terminal LFW experienced a release of "UN1993 Ethylhexl nitrate". It was reported that during dock operations terminal personnel forked a 275 gallon tote causing an approximate 15 gallon release impacting trailer and dock floor. It was reported no drains, soils or waterways were impacted the release. Terminal personnel placed dry absorbents around the poly tote and tilted it on its side to contain the release.Due to the need of a tote transfer, a contractor was dispatched. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed the release amount of approximately 15-gallons impacted a 15' x 24' area of dock floor and beneath the trailer outside of dock area. Absorbents will applied to impacted areas and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The contractor neutralized impacted areas and washed down areas. The impacted rinse water was containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum and the impacted absorbents were containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. All waste was staged for the terminal to manage proper disposal.

column168: May 5, 2019 at 0635 ET A Trimac tractor trailer experienced a single vehicle accident resulting in a loss of cargo on I-20 in Stanton, TX. It was reported that an unknown amount of Red Dye Diesel released impacting the roadway and soil shoulder. The extent of the release was unknown at the initial time. Trimac dispatched a relief tank to the site. ERTS spoke with the driver who reported the unit slid causing 3 or 4 welds to crack. The tank was carrying ~7700 gallons. ERTS has dispatched Talon LPE to respond and perform containment and cleanup activities. Talon LPE arrived onsite and assessed the release. They estimated the release to have been 5000 gallon of diesel fuel which impacted the road way, soil shoulder and 100 ft of a ditch line which leads to a drain. Talon LPE confirmed the material impacted the drain. A vacuum truck was used to recover the lost material in the drain while a skid steer was used on the roadway and soil to recover the majority of the material. The site was secured for further remediation.

Covenant notified ERTS of a cargo release. column168: On May 23, 2019 at 06:38 EST, XPO Logistics NRM terminal experienced a UN1263 "Epoxy Primer Coating Kit" release from one fiberboard box containing four (4) I-gallon metal cans. All the release was contained to trailer 6996424 floor. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by the release. After reviewing the SDS it was determined that due to the strong odor a contractor would be dispatched. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of UN1263 released to a 4' x 12' area of the trailer floor. column168: PACKAGE WAS FOUND IN AN AIR CAN WITH A GASH IN THE SIDE AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID LEAKING OUT. PACKAGE WAS TAKEN ASIDE AND CLEANED UP.

BNSF S. Seattle Hub Operations notified LARS of top stack unit FDXU 532139 that was observed to be leaking a dark liquid seeping through the container floor and onto the bottom container and rail car UCRY 57367 at the destination SSE Ramp. Unit is billed as containing mixed FAK with a corrosive hazardous material and as such, ramp operations were shut down and a 150ft perimeter was cleared until the leak could be assessed; NRC Environmental was contacted and responded to remediate. Inspection revealed the leak to be a liquid tote of cleaning compound containing corrosive contents, and it appears that the plastic tank imploded downward and then expanded outward laterally from some unknown means (possibly temperature related), breaking pieces off of the surrounding metal cage and damaging the bottom valve which caused the leaking condition observed. NRC is still in the process of cleaning and remediation, as well as pumping the remaining liquid from the damaged tote into a new one.

column168: On May 22, 2019 at 05:00 EST, XPO logistics (UKC) experienced a hazardous cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading from previous terminal USL, approximately 12- ounces of hazardous UN2265 "Dimethylformamide" (3), III released from a stainless steel metal tote weighing 3300 lbs. The caller indicated the released product is leaking slow but is contained to the trailer floor of trailer #3177532. Due to the size of the container, ERTS will dispatch a contractor to clean and manage spill. The tote was actively leaking and personnel were unable to plug container to prevent further release. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed that approximately 15-20 gallons of material has now released impacting a inside trailer and a 35' x 4' area beneath trailer. The remaining product in damaged container was transferred into seven (7) 55-gallon steel drums at the request of the shipper, they will provide labels and will continue with the delivery. Contractor applied absorbents to the impacted areas under trailer and trailer, including impacted pallets. All spent absorbents and debris were containerized into one (1) 55-gallon steel drum and staged in OS&D area for terminal to manage proper disposal.

column168: Release of 150 gallons Nitric B (PC 737100).  All contained on customer site and treated onsite.         On 5/15/2019 at approximately 12:50PM, driver was in the early process of offloading Nitric B when he noticed product spraying from top of trailer.  Driver proceeded to shut down air and close valves. The facility was evacuated.  Fire Department responded.  UnivarSolutions emergency spill response contractor NRC Environmental was contacted to clean up the spill.  RRM notified followed with 2-hour release notification sent. Oregon Emergency Response System (OERS) notified. No injuries or exposures reported.   Investigation findings determined the cause of the release was due to failed gasket material of construction that was not compatible to Nitric Acid  (EPDM vs. teflon/goretex).
column169: Truck maintenance shop to address training issues with crew, insert equipment specific gasket requirements along with annual gasket change outs.   Equipment to be overhauled to include vapor lines replacement, gasket change out, changes in air actuator switches, installation of additional emergency shut-off switches.

On May 30, 2019 at 03:20, XPO Logistics  terminal USB in regards to a regulated release of "UN3109 peroxy x22". It was reported that terminal personnel discovered a 55-gallon plastic drum that had a loose cap inside of trailer #3117361. Reportedly releasing 3 ounces of its product to the floor of the trailer. Due to the odor of the product terminal personnel have requested a contractor to clean and contain the release. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed 3-ounces of material has released from three (3) 55-gallon drums due loose caps. The caps were loosened to relieve the pressure and then re-tightened. All material was contained to tops of the drums, the drums were wiped down. The spent absorbent rags used to wipe down drums were placed into a 15-gallon poly drum and staged in the OS&D area for the terminal to manage proper disposal.

On May 17, 2019 at 0515 EST, XPO Logistics LHW terminal experienced a UN1760, Corrosive Liquid, N.O.S., 8, PGII release. It was reported that due to improper loading the 5-gallon containers tipped up. All release was contained to trailer 3119413 floor. Due to the material hazards a contractor was dispatched to site. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed that thirty-nine 5-gallon pails tipped over due to pails not being strapped to pallet. It was confirmed that no containers were damaged just leaked due to being tipped over. Contractors wiped down impacted container, pallet and applied granular absorbents to impacted trailer floor. The spent absorbents were recovered and placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum and staged in OS&D area for terminal to manage proper disposal. The container were re-palletized and shrink wrapped to continue with shipment.

column168: On May 21, 2019 at 0605 EST, XPO Logistics (UKC) experienced a cargo release.  According to the caller, approximately 1/2 cup of  regulated UN1789 "Hydrochloric Acid" released from a 55 gallon poly drum due to the cap being damaged to a trailer floor (3175391). Due to the hazardous properties of the product and the terminal not having a new cap to replace the damaged cap a contractor was dispatched. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1/2 cup released impacting the top of the drum due to damage to cap from no blocking and bracing. They applied neutralizer to the top of the drum and transferred the material into a new 55-gallon poly drum to continue with shipment. The damaged drum was cut up and placed into a 55-gallon poly drum and placed in the OS&D area for terminal to manage proper disposal.

column168: Vehicle was traveling south on SR-191 nearing mile marker 257 when vehicle rounded the last of a series of sharp s turns, bearing right, the tractor and lead trailer were coming out to the turn when the pup trailer tipped over causing the lead trailer and tractor to overturn along with the pup trailer.  When the pup trailer tipped on its side it struck the guard rail which punctured the tank and allowed product to spill.   Contacted 911 and they were dispatched along with the carbon county hazmat team to contain any additional spillage.  Tow company removed equipment and Envirocare was contracted to clean up the spilled product with the overside of the EPA and Utah DEQ.   Cleanup has been completed and meets the approval of these departments.
column169: Exact cause of incident is unknown, driver was not cited nor was it equipment failure.  Because of the sharpness of the turn it is possible the product may have shifted to left front of the pup trailer while rounding the corner causing the pup trailer to overturn.  More driver education on hauling a liquid load and well as slower speeds in sharp corners may have prevented the incident

column168: On May 22, 2019 at 19:00, XPO logistics XCM experienced a cargo release. column168: On May 18, 2019 the BNSF South Seattle Hub reported unit CTTZ738234 leaking at destination. The waybill listed 2 Hazardous commodities:  1) UN2922 Corrosive Liquid, Hydroflouric Acid 2,879LBS;  2) UN1075 Petroleum Gases, Liquefied, 154LBS.   The unit was moved to the containment area for evaluation by hazmat response, NRC Environmental. Per Emergency Response Guide, a 150 isolation perimeter was established. NRC arrived and observed the leak was from an IBC tote of "Quick Silver Concentrate". Cause of the leak was the result of the cap unsecured/not applied. The cap was observed off to the side of the opening which allowed fluid to escape. Estimated volume loss of approximately 1 pint.  NRC remediated portions of the railcar where product escaped the trailer. NRC unloaded the tote and remediated the exterior of the tote and relevant portions of the trailer. Release estimates are based upon the best information available from responders.

column168: On 5/15/19 at appx 1400, Gilbert Medrano was involved in a rollover accident on NV-766 N about 8 miles north of Carlin, NV. Front right steer tire of Truck 112 went off asphalt and onto soft shoulder at a left-hand curve in the road. Driver corrected truck, but front trailer (BAT4) and rear trailer (PAT203) caught soft dirt on right-hand side and pulled truck and trailers off the road resulting in vehicle rollover. Truck remained on solid ground but both trailers ended up in adjacent Maggie Creek. Trailer BAT4 breached and released sulfuric acid into Maggie Creek. Gilbert believes his speed at the time of the accident was 45MPH.   Trailer BAT4 was punctured at some point during the rollover. It is believed that the "tongue" or tow assembly of the "pup" trailer (PAT203) is what punctured the vessel. The puncture is an appx 8" diameter hole towards the top of the tank near the rib above the front axle of the trailer.  The exact duration of the release is unknown. BJ Cecil Trucking contacted National Interstate Insurance upon being informed of the crash. National Interstate contracted Cura Emergency Services to initiate emergency response. Cura Emergency Services contracted Enviro Care, Inc. to respond to scene of incident.  Trailer BAT4 was extracted from Maggie Creek at appx 2100.
column169: Gilbert Medrano has been required to undergo a reevaluation of driving skills and a retraining period before returning to full duty.

column168: On 5/16/19 at approximately 8:00 AM, a leaking 55 gallon drum of corrosive liquids with Ethanolamine was discovered to be slowly leaking.  It was on a trailer over night on 5/15/19 at the Veolia 10 day  in-transit facility located in Schenectady, NY.  It is estimated that approximately 4 gallons leaked  over night and was discovered when employees reported to the office on the morning of 5/16/19.   After the leaking container was discovered, the spill was contained, cleaned up, and the 55 gallon  drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum.  During the overpacking process, the leak  became worse and an additional 2 gallons of material leaked out during handling.  All liquids that  leaked were cleaned up with absorbent materials and placed in drums for disposal.  The leaking  container was placed in an overpack and transported to the final disposal facility.  The drum was in poor condition and did not appear to have a proper UN certification on it.  The  certification may have corroded or may not have been present when the drum was originally  manufactured and filled with hazardous materials.  It was observed that the corrosion was especially  bad on the bottom of the steel drum and was the location of the leak.  There was a discussion about the rust on the container at the time of initial shipment and the  offeror felt that the drum was safe to ship as it was without overpacking at the time of pick up. The discussion was between a Veolia employee and an employee of the offeror.
column169: Veolia notified the offeror of the shipment about the hazardous material release.  Veolia told the  employee that the drum should have been overpacked prior to shipment.  In addition, the Veolia EH&S group notified the Veolia employee who took possession of the  shipment and his manager that the container should have never been accepted for transportation in the condition it was in.  Veolia EH&S explained that the container was in poor condition and did  not have an identifiable UN certification.  The container should have been overpacked at the offeror's  location prior to being placed in transportation.  Training with Veolia employees was performed on 6/5/19 to prevent this from happening again.   Pictures of the leaking container and the DOT requirements for packages to be in good condition and to have UN certification marking prior to shipping were also reviewed during the retraining  session.

column168: DRIVER STATEMENT: ON 5/23/2019, I LOADED 5,500 GALLONS OF REGULAR AND 3,000 GALLONS OUT OF THE MAGELLAN 2 LOADING RACK IN NASHVILLE, TN. I WAS TAKING THAT LOAD TO THE MURPHY'S IN WAVERLY, VIA SR-70. THIS GENERAL AREA IS A TWO LANE ROAD, POORLY LIT WITH HILLS AND CURVES. AT THIS POINT, I GENTLY MOVED THE TRUCK CLOSER TO THE WHITE LINE TO AVOID IT. I FELT AN AVERAGE SIZE BUMP, THAN A HARD-PULLING SENSATION THAT SENT ME ONTO THE SOFT SHOULDER. I WOULD DESCRIBE THIS FEELING SIMILAR TO A BLOWN STEER TIRE. I LET OFF THE THROTLE AND ATTEMPTED TO STEER BACK ONTO THE ROAD, BUT THE SHOULDER WAS MUCH STEEPER THAN I THOUGHT. THE TRUCK WAS PUSHED BACK OFF THE SHOULDER AND HIT A DRIVEWAY "HUMP". ONCE I HIT THE DRIVEWAY MY TRUCK BOUNCED VERY HARD AND PULLED INTO THE DEEP DITCH THAT FOLLOWED THE DRIVEWAY. MY TRUCK ROLLED AND ENDED UP ON THE ROOF, MY SEAT HAD TURNED 180 DEGREES PINCHING MY LEFT LEG UNDER/BEHIND THE SEAT. THE DIESEL COMPARTMENT #1, HAD BUSTED OPEN AND FUEL WAS RUSHING INTO THE CAB, THANKFULLY IT STOPPED A FEW INCHES UNDER MY HEAD. MY PHONE FLEW AND WAS THROWN FROM THE UNIT, IN AN ATTEMPT TO CALL FOR HELP I WAS ABLE TO REACH THE STEERING WHEEL HORN IN HOPES SOMEONE COULD HEAR ME. UNFORTUNATELY, THIS IS A VERY RURAL ROAD WITH VERY LITTLE TRAFFIC AT THIS TIME OF THE MORNING. I STRUGGLED TO FREE MY LEG AND SOON ENDED UP PASSING OUT DUE TO FUMES AND PAIN. I WOKE BACK UP TO FIREFIGHTERS ON SCENE. AFTER WORKING FOR MORE THAN 2 HOURS, THE EMERGENCY CREW CUT ME FROM THE UNIT AROUND 3:45 AM AND LIE FLIGHTED ME TO VANDERBILT HOSPITAL IN NASHVILLE, TN, FOR TREATMENT.
column169: REVIEW ALL COMPANY STANDARDS OR TRAINING AND DRIVING TECHNIQUE. TEAM STANDARDS ARE 2 YEARS MINIMUM DRIVING WITH NO MORE THAN ONE VIOLATION IN THE PAST THREE YEARS. FOLLOW UP WITH ALL COMPANY DRIVERS IN MONTHLY SAFETY MEETINGS ON THE FINDINGS FROM THIS CRASH AND APPLY SMITH SYSTEM TRAINING AGAIN.

column168: On 05/31/2019 at 1924hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Chicago 59th ILL Terminal discovered SNLU996903, a loaded container of 7pcs UN1824, Sodium Hydroxide Solution, 8, II, in 330gallon plastic totes with aluminum cage, leaked 15gals of liquid from rear of container onto asphalt pavement. The container was isolated and ILL EMA was notified, report#H-2019-0550.  The shipper, Schneider National Inc, representative was notified by CSXI Customer Service, case#365706. CSXT emergency response contractor, SUNPRO Services, was dispatched to the scene and found one tote released three-quarters of contents onto trailer floor. Release was due to loadshift  puncturing tote at bottom seams. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the leak by transfer of product into recovery tote, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the release site. The original freight container with highway load/block/brace was released to the shipper.  This incident did not require a special switching move. This incident did not require a Form 7.1..

The pressure vent opened to vent the trailer and product was released due to the position of the front vs rear of the trailer.

column168: The material that was involved in the incident was lead acid batteries with the terminals located on the side.  The batteries were secured to a wooden pallet and secured with plastic wrap.  The terminals of  the batteries were protected with tape to prevent short circuits.  The batteries were transferred from  one truck to another.  During the transfer process the plastic protecting the battery terminals was  abraded by the side wall of the trailer resulting in a small hole in the plastic wrap exposing one of the terminals.  The trailer walls had metal supports in the structure and when the exposed terminals came in contact with the metal it started to smolder/smoke.  A fire extinguisher was used to prevent a  bigger incident and the pallet of batteries was removed from the truck.  The batteries were repackaged to include a protective border consisting of cardboard in addition to the plastic wrap to protect the  battery terminals.
column169: To prevent a reoccurrence, Veolia will follow a new procedure when managing batteries that have side  terminals.  The terminals will be protected against short circuit by using tape or rubberized spray.   In addition, cardboard frames with a plastic fiber outer material will be used to further protect the  terminals and tape/rubber coating from abrasion.

ERTS will coordinated disposal with the contractor.

column168: On May 9, 2019 at 06:50 EST, XPO Logistics (XAK) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to unknown circumstances, approximately 50 gallons of Organic Peroxide Type F (Hazardous - UN3109) was released from 1-275 gallon poly tote. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor, asphalt floor and possibly at the cross section of 289 & Campbellsville bypass (3350 & 289 intersection). The caller is requesting a contractor due to the hazardous state and size of the spill.  The terminal advised local Fire Department are onsite and have blocked off area of terminal due to strong odor. Contractor arrived onsite and advised per the Fire Dept, there was gas emitting through the top of the trailer and corrosive material has eaten thru the bottom of the trailer. ERTS communicated with all state regulatory divisions. Contractor stated that near by houses were evacuated at the time of the spill. A intersection of road way was used as a command area., at this time the road way has been re-opened and the civilians have been aloud to return to the homes. Air monitoring equipment has been set up. The clean team is in level B and is working on keeping the product contained. The contractor is closely monitoring O2 levels inside the trailer. The floor of the trailer is wood and there is concern that the product could react and ignite. Contractor removed the undamaged totes from the trailer. Approximately 130 gallons of product released to the gravel lot, drainage ditch and grass. Contractor gravity transferred the rest of the product into a new 275-gallon tote. The original tote was punctured by a hook in the trailer. The contractor utilized absorbents to clean up the release in the trailer. The contractor has boomed off the trailer, ditch, and impacted grass.The contractor returned to the site follow day to complete cleanup and remediate the impacted soil. Contractor arrived follow day and excavated impacted soil, grass and gravel loaded to transport for disposal. Five drums of impacted absorbents were generated and staged in OS&D for the terminal to manage proper disposal.

column168: At approximately 1030 hours Central Standard Time, a a Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. driver noticed liquid on the inside floor of the trailer while performing a routine load inspection prior to departure from the shipper. Absorbent material was immediately put down the spent product was contained. An in-house response crew responded to the spill, donned the appropriated PPE, and cleaned up the spill. Spilled material and absorbent materials used to remediate the spill were properly packaged, marked, and labeled and sent for disposal.
column169: An investigation into the spill incident revealed that the puncture was due to a sharp object contacting the container during the loading process. Dock personnel were retrained on proper vehicle floor inspections before the loading process.

column168: While loading, (1) - (5)gal jug was punctured and leaking due to a nail sticking out of the skid. (2)cups of material released.
column169: More training for drivers to better inspect freight and skids before accepting from the shipper.

column168: During routine facility inspections, a container was identified as having a release. An internal emergency response team was dispatched to assist. In appropriate personal protective equipment, verified through the internal health and safety department, the team was able to safely repackage the compromised container into approved UN rated containers appropriate for the material. The impact of this release was contained to secondary containment, with no threat or impact to land, soil, water ways or storm drains. The material was shipped to its final destination without further incident.
column169: The generator was notified of the release and advised on container selection appropriate for the material.

column168: At approximately 2115 hours, a Safety Kleen Corp. dock employee was unloading a vehicle which had been previously staged at the dock area for offloading. While unloading other palletized containers, the forklift tines of the forklift the employee was operating, inadvertently punctured two drums which were staged to be offloaded resulting in the release. Absorbent material was immediately put down the spent product was contained. An in-house response crew responded to the spill, donned the appropriated PPE, and cleaned up the spill. Spilled material and absorbent materials used to remediate the spill were properly packaged, marked, and labeled and sent for disposal.
column169: An investigation into the spill incident revealed that the puncture was due to the tines of the forklift contacting the container during the offloading process. The dock employee was retrained on proper forklift operation.

column168: On May 17, 2019, at 1050 ET, Schneider National notified ERTS of a release of an unknown amount of UN1866 "Branched PE" from a 275 gallon metal tote. ERTS Dispatched E3 Environmental to conduct all on site remediation activities. At 1130 ET, contractors arrived on site and confirmed approximately 1 gallon released to a 4' x 4' area of the trailer, a 2' x 2' area of the concrete. Contractors identified the point of release from the ball valve and the cam lock cap as they were left open and not fully secured in the closed position. Granular absorbents were worked into the impacted trailer and concrete and then containerized for disposal.  At 1709 ET, Schneider personnel notified ERTS of an impacted soil area. At 1752 ET, contractors returned to the site to excavate the impacted soil area. The soil was hand dug and placed into a second drum for disposal. Contractors completed cleanup and departed site at 1800 ET.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING DIESEL FUEL IN TO AN UNDERGROUND TANK WHEN THE FILL SPOUT CAME LOOSE FROM THE TANK. THIS RESULTED IN A 1123 GALLON DIESEL FUEL SPILL ON TO A GRAVEL PARKING LOT. WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SITE. THEY WERE ON SITE WITHIN 10 MINUTES. THEY DUG UP APPROXIMATELY 150 YARDS OF CONTAMINATED DIRT. THIS DIRT WAS STOCK PILED ON A PLASTIC TARP AND THE PILE WAS ALSO COVERED WITH PLASTIC UNTIL THE CONTAMINATED SOIL CAN BE BROUGHT TO A LANDFILL. THE DUG OUT AREA WAS FILLED IN THE NEW CLASS 5 GRAVEL. WCEC IS WAITING FOR THE LAB RESULTS ON THE SOIL TO DETERMINE WHICH LANDFILL WILL ACCEPT THE MATERIAL. AS SOON AS THOSE RESULTS COME BACK, WE WILL MOVE FORWARD WITH DISPOSING OF THE SOIL AT AN APPROPRIATE LAND FILL SITE.  THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS A DEFECTIVE FILL SPOUT. THAT SPOUT WAS DISPOSED OF AND REPLACED WITH A NEW ONE THAT VERY AFTERNOON.

column168: IBC of Barrage HF (2,4-D Ester herbicide) was picked up from a farm field where it had been used for field application. The pump and hose remained affixed to the IBC. During transport to the Carthage facility, the driver noticed liquid leaving his truck and immediately stopped. He discovered the hose from the IBC to the pump had come loose. The bottom discharge valve on the IBC was not properly closed prior to shipping. The driver secured the valve and continued on his delivery. He returned within 30 minutes to clean up the spilled liquid. The next day, a clean up contractor (Clean Harbors) was contacted to complete the cleanup of the herbicide residue from the roadway. Note: initial report to NRC indicated Charlottesville (Hancock Co), IN was nearest city; after report, determined Carthage (Rush Co), IN was closest city to incident location.
column169: Typically the bottom discharge valve handle is properly closed prior to shipping. In order to ensure valves are checked and closed, all IBCs will have zip ties added to the hoses to ensure they do not come loose when moving the IBC.

column168: During routine transportation activities, the driver pulled over to do an inspection and identified a release coming from the nose of the transport trailer. The driver called for assistance and an emergency response team was dispatched. Several local authorities, including the fire department, police, highway patrol and homeland security came to the scene. The LA Department of Environmental Quality performed air monitoring surrounding the trailer to ensure a safe environment for entry. After several hours the response team was able to safely enter the trailer and identify the compromised container. There was impact to the soil adjacent to the highway at a space of approximately 12x12'. At the direction of the local authorities, the release was contained sufficiently enough to allow the unit to move off the highway to facilitate the remediation of the trailer and overpack the compromised container. Once the trailer and containers were cleaned to the approval of local authorities, the trailer was sent  to its final destination without further incident. LA State Report number 19-02296 and LA State Police Report numbers H19-0067, H19-0068 have been received from authorities as a result of this release.
column169: An internal investigation into the root cause of this release immediately commenced. Senior leadership and compliance departments participated to analyze the situation, identify the cause and subsequent root causes and formulated corrective actions. This investigation and remediation of impacted soils is still active. This report will be amended as needed.

While making a delivery to North Texas Water Municipalities, a driver tried to avoid a wreck when a car cut in front of him causing him to loose control and collide with two other vehicles, a passenger car and 18-wheeler.  This caused damage to the tanker and resulted in the release of 25% Sodium Hydroxide solution onto the roadway.  Petra contacted contractor, TAS Environmental Services, to clean up the area.  Once it was determined the RQ had been exceeded, the NRC and TCEQ were contacted by corporate EHSS personnel.  The clean-up operations were already underway.  Dallas HazMat was onsite and placed a containment basin under the leaking tanker.  Since it was storming, they were pumping the material back into the damaged tanker as basin filled. TAS arrived on scene and transferred the caustic from damaged tanker into another one brought by Petra.  They also collected 4 X 55-gallon drums of contaminated sorbents from the area.  TAS personnel met with regulators to determine the scope of the work needed.  As a result, the area was cleaned with water and pH samples taken randomly from different areas to confirm neutralization.  The sodium hydroxide solution pumped into the other tanker was re-processed at Petra's facility and sold.

column168: A brake failure on the trailer started a fire at the rear of the trailer. After not being able to extinguish the fire with a fire extinguisher, the driver called 911 and moved the semi-tractor to a safe location. The fire ended up engulfing the entire trailer causing the bung caps to blow off the 55 gallon drums. Upon arriving, the remediation crew reported approximately 300 gallons of paint mixed with water released to the trailer interior, asphalt surfaces below, and into a soil drainage ditch adjacent to the roadway.  After discussing the remediation with the on-site representative from the Virginia Department of Emergency Management (VDEM), the remediation crew deployed absorbent booms to contain the release in the drainage ditch and then utilized a vacuum truck to collect the pain-impacted water from the drainage ditch and the trailer interior. The crew then deployed granular absorbents to the paint-impacted asphalt surfaces and worked it in with machinery. All paint-impacted material was then collected in roll-off containers. They then covered the paint-impacted soil with poly sheeting and deployed additional absorbent boom in the drainage ditch as a precautionary measure. The crew returned at a later date to finish the remediation of which we have not received a final report.

column168: On May 14, 2019, at 0145 ET, a Dupre Logistics tanker was involved in a single vehicle accident causing the unit to roll over into a ditch line.  At 0335 ET, Dupre Logistics contacted Emergency Response and Training Solutions to manage and oversee environmental remediation. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental to conduct all spill response operations. At 0900 ET, E3 Environmental personnel arrived on site. At 1010 ET, contractors reported a slow drip from one of the compartments. The unit was bonded, grounded, and the pumps and hoses were attached. At 1333 ET. contractor reported that as two of the compartments were drilled, approximately 100 gallons of gasoline released from the dome lid to the ditch. Boom was utilized to contain the release. A vacuum truck was utilized to collect the water from the ditch. At 1710 ET, contractors cleaned the roadway and skimmed the gasoline impacted water from the ditch. The site was then secured and all waste was transported off site for proper disposal.

column168: On May 14, 2019 at 2200 ET, Landstar Ranger experienced a cargo release. It was reported that the Landstar driver has a leaking 250 gallon poly tote of haz UN1908 Chlorite Solution 14% inside his trailer. Cause of the release is unknown at this time. The driver is currently on route to the Flying J Truck stop in Big Springs, NE. The driver has 11 totes in the trailer and he believes 1 tote is damaged and needs a transfer. Contractor arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 45 gallons of product was released in total from a 330-gallon tote which was only filled with 275 gallons of product. It was advised that a 8' x 20' gravel area under the trailer was impacted by. Contractor personnel applied soda ash to neutralize and absorbent pads to recover material. The material remaining in damaged tote was transferred to new tote. Generated waste drum were staged onsite pending disposal completion.

Driver was unable to get a full load of butane because the facility ran out the night before. He had loaded 7,257 gallons of butane in the lead trailer and had an empty pup and headed to Heber that night to complete his 10 hour reset. The next morning, he was headed from Heber, UT, going toward Basin Western - N. Salt Lake shop when he came around a curve at 62 mph with cruise control set and jake brakes on. The pup trailer (empty) started to shift and driver gently hit brakes to disengage cruise control. The pup tipped over to the right and the driver applied more brake pressure and tried to turn the wheel to get back on the road. The pup went on it's side and pulled the lead trailer and truck over. Driver lost control of the truck, it fell on it's side, slid off the road into the dirt, over the guardrail and into Deer Creek Reservoir. Police, fire and ambulance were called to respond, as well as Basin Western dispatch and safety team. The driver was taken to nearest hospital for evaluation and testing. Basin Western initiated calls with their insurance agency, Great West Casualty, to involve them in the emergency response. A towing company was called to retrieve the truck and trailers from the water. The butane that was on the lead trailer was trans-loaded onto another trailer and delivered to the original destination (Delta, Utah). Some diesel fuel from the truck had leaked into the water and LMH Environmental Inc. was called and various other hazmat crews were required to contain and clean up any spilled/leaked diesel from the reservoir and monitor for possible butane contamination and to take samples of the reservoir water. Barricades were put up and road closure was necessary while the clean up and towing efforts were taking place. The truck and trailers had been extracted early the next morning. Most of the environmental restoration work was completed by 5/30/19 and water samples were good. Booms were left in place over the weekend and the final check was done on Monday, June 3rd.
column169: There was a slight variance to the driver's normal routine due to the fact that the pup was empty, and that may have contributed to the accident. He normally would have had a full load and possibly have had better control of the trailers when going around the curve. The driver was issued a citation for speeding which was also a determining factor. Basin Western management and safety compliance teams conducted an accident review with the driver on Tuesday, June 4th. It was determined that the driver was not paying attention to the posted speed limits, was driving too fast to negotiate the corner and should not have been using cruise control on that section of the highway. Basin Western has stepped up its safety efforts to focus on awareness of surroundings when driving, speeding policies, and adapting policy and precautionary procedures when hauling an empty pup trailer.

column168: Driver loaded crude oil at a lease off of Peterson Road, departed and when he stopped at a red light in town he saw some oil dripping down the side of his trailer. He stopped and secured the scene notifying local authorities and company. He placed absorbent pads on roadway where oil had spilled. Local police closed the roadway, the township public works brought out sand/dirt to absorb spilled oil as well. A response team was called to clean up the spilled area and contaminated absorbent for disposal. The cargo tank had been washed out and some repair work completed on it by a third party vendor. After the repairs they had not secured the dome lid and washout caps on top. The oil had spilled on the roadway for approximately 200 feet and remained on the roadway.
column169: Proper procedures were reviewed with the vendor on closing and securing caps and closures after washout and repairs. Reviewed with employees proper cap/closure verification procedures to be taken when they pick up a cargo tank trailer after repairs/washouts/inspections prior to placing back into service.

column168: On May 31, 2019 at 2330 ET, Landstar Inway experienced a spill at Flying J Travel Center located at 9351 Canal Rd, Gulfport, MS 39503. Driver of Landstar Ranger Truck #425452/ trailer #825452 discovered the release of approximately 1 quart of an unknown hazmat in the trailer.  At 2353 ET, ERTS dispatched Hepaco with an ETA of 90 mins. At 0024 ET, ERTS provided the driver with an ETA, the driver stated that he noticed the release during his routine check. 0150 ET, Contractor located the damaged drum, 1-55 gallon metal drum of UN1993-Flammable liquid that was punctured at the bottom by a wooden box. Approximately 5 gallons released to a 10 ft X 5 ft area of the trailer floor and a 1 ft X 5 ft area of the concrete lot. , the release was cleaned up with granular absorbents. Contractor transferred the product from the damaged drum into a 55-gallon metal drum, the contractor also generated another 55-gallon metal drum of impacted absorbents. Contractor departed the site with the generated waste and damaged drum to be disposed of at a later date.
FORKLIFT PUNCTURED IBC TOTE DURING UNLOADING AT THE ESTES HOUSTON, TX TERMINAL. USES, A QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, WAS IMMEDIATELY ENGAGED TO CONDUCT ALL GROUND CLEANUP AND STORM DRAIN CLEANUP.
column169: ALL FORKLIFT DRIVER ARE TRAINED IN PROPER FORKLIFT OPERATIONS.

column168: At 1100 ET, ERTS was notified by Evan Bartlett of XPO (XSY) regarding a cargo release. According to the caller, approximately 2-oz. of hazardous UN 2794 "Wet field battery " released to the trailer floor due to tilting over caused by improper loading. The caller indicated the release was contained to the trailer floor . The terminal requested a contractor to clean the spill and provide proper containers needed to complete the clean up. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. There is regulatory reporting required for the release. ERTS will upload the BOL, SDS and create a waste container entry once contractor access clean up. // Clean harbors has been dispatched with an ETA of 60 minutes. ERTS notified NYDEC, Operator 32, provided report #1901694 to the incident. The contractor clean the spill with soda ash and other absorbents. All waste was placed into a 55gal poly drum and left on site.

column168: THIS UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED BY THE FEDEX CUSTOMS BROKER IN TOLUCA, MEXICO. THE PACKAGE HAD A SMALL SPILL. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS WERE 3 PAINT CANS AND A SAFETY DATA SHEET SHOWING THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME OF PAINT IN THE TRANSPORT SECTION. AS THE OUTER PACKAGING DID NOT HAVE ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELS OR PAPERWORK IT’S UNDECLARED DG. THIS WAS A RETURN TO SENDER SHIPMENT TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER OF THE PACKAGE FROM MEMPHIS HUB. I HAVE NOT BEEN ABLE TO CONFIRM WITH THE EMPLOYEE'S MANAGER IF THEY SIMPLY REPLACED THE WAYBILL WITH THE NEW AUTOMATION LABEL BUT NEVER OPENED OR REPLACED THE SHIPMENT OR IF THEY HAD SEEN THE INNER CONTENTS. IF THEY REPLACED THE AUTOMATION LABEL ONLY WITHOUT SEEING THE CONTENTS ALTHOUGH FEDEX EXPRESS IS LISTED AS THE SHIPPER ON THE AUTOMATION LABEL THE UNDECLARED DG WOULD NOT BE FEDEX EXPRESS MAY HAVE HAD SOME RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE CAUSE OF THE UNDECLARED DG. MY SAFETY COUNTERPART IN MEXICO REPORTED THIS SHIPMENT TO THE COMPETENT AUTHORITY LOCALLY THERE. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AT DESTINATION PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED TO FAA VIA EMAIL ON 5/24/19
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: AT START OF UNLOADING OPERATION VALVE AT STORAGE TANK REQUIRED REPLACEMENT DUE TO PRESSURIZED LEAK WHICH SPRAYED DRIVERS PPE. ONCE CONSIGNEE’S PERSONNEL REPLACED VALVE AT STORAGE TANK UNLOADING CONTINUE. DURING SECOND ATTEMPT TO UNLOAD REPLACEMENT VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY INSTALLED AND RESULTED IN PRODUCT SPRAYING ON DRIVER WHO WAS NOW WITHOUT FULL PPE PROTECTION. DRIVER SPRAYED ON THE RIGHT SIDE UNDER FACIAL DOWN TO HIS FOOT. DRIVER SPRAYED BY CONSIGNEE'S PERSONNEL WITH WATER AS MATERIAL WAS PG II CLASS 8. DRIVER PLACED ON LIGHT DUTY FOR ONE DAY TO VERIFY NO SUSTAINED INJURY.
column169: DRIVER RETRAINED IN REQUIREMENTS FOR PPE AT ALL TIMES WHEN LOADING OR UNLOADING ANY CLASS 8 MATERIAL. CONSIGNEE INSTRUCTED TO RETRAIN PERSONNEL ON PROPER INSTALLATION OF VALVES AND DEVICES USED IN THE UNLOADING OPERATIONS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED BY THE FEDEX CUSTOMS BROKER IN MEXICO. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS WERE 2 PLASTIC INNER CONTAINERS. ONE HAD DG MARKINGS AND LABELING FOR UN 3105, ORGANIC PEROXIDE TYPE D LIQUID. DIVISION 5.2. THE OTHER ITEM IS UN 1263 PAINT RELATED MATERIAL. THE OUTLET BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELS OR PAPERWORK. ALTHOUGH THE SHIPPER LISTED ON THE AUTOMATION LABEL AS FEDEX EXPRESS, THIS WAS A RETURN TO SENDER SHIPMENT TO THE CUSTOMER IN MEXICO FROM AN EMPLOYEE IN THE MEMPHIS HUB. I WAS UNABLE TO CONFIRM WITH THE EMPLOYEE’S MANAGER WHETHER OR NOT THE EMPLOYEE SIMPLY REPLACED THE AUTOMATION LABEL ON THE OUTER BOX WITHOUT OPENING THE BOX AND SEEING THE CONTENTS OR REPACKAGING IT OR IF THEY DID REPACK AND SEE THE CONTENTS WITH THE DG MARKINGS AND LABELS. IF THEY DID NOT OPEN THE PACKAGE THE UNDECLARED DG WAS NOT CAUSED BY FEDEX EXPRESS. HOWEVER, IF THEY DID OPEN THE PACKAGE FEDEX EXPRESS MAY HAVE HAD SOME ROLE IN THE CAUSE OF THE UNDECLARED DG. MY SAFETY COUNTERPART IN MEXICO REPORTED THE SHIPMENT TO THE LOCAL COMPETENT AUTHORITY. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AT THE DESTINATION PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED OF THE UNDECLARED DG VIA EMAIL ON 5/24/2019

column168: On May 31, 2019 at 1020 EST, ERTS was contacted by Dohrn Transfer- Pitt Ohio regarding a hazardous cargo release. It was reported that there was a release of UN3266, Corrosive liquid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s., (Sodium hydroxide, sodium hypochlorite), 8, PGII "Sodium hydroxide".  The terminal requested a contractor be dispatched to respond. At 1410 EST, the contractor arrived on site and confirmed that approximately 25 gallons of product had released to a 10' x 7' area of the trailer due to what the contractor believed to be a weak spot in the 55-gallon poly drum causing a pin hole leak due to the heat. The contractor placed absorbents on the impacted area and swept them into poly waste drums. The absorbents, spent PPE, impacted pallet pieces and other debris were all placed into (4) 55-gallon poly waste drums. The damaged drum was placed inside (1) 95-gallon poly overpack drum.

column168: Hawaiian Airlines (HAL) received a US Mail package for transport from LAX-HNL on 05/21/2019. The the final destination of the package was Lahaina, Maui.  HAL received the package in LAX and transported the package to HNL on HA5.  Upon receipt in HNL the package was damaged and it was discovered to contain loose ammunition.  The word "Tools" was written on the front of the package.  The item is prohibited from being accepted and transported on HAL and via the USPS.  The package was turned over to the USPIS in HNL. A photograph of the damage box and ammunition is included with this report.
column169: The root cause of the incident resulted from the package not being properly screened and segregated at the USPS in AZ and LAX.

column168: Hawaiian Airlines (HAL) received a US Mail package for transport from LAX-KOA on 05/22/2019. The  final destination of the package was Narita, Japan. HAL received the package in LAX and transported the package to KOA on HA61. Upon receipt in KOA it was discovered that the package contained a "surface transportation label" and "Lithium Ion Battery" label. The item is prohibited from being accepted and transported on HAL and via the USPS. The package was turned over to the USPIS in KOA on 5/30/2019.  A copy of the incident report provided to USPS and photographs have been included with the report.
column169: The root cause of the incident resulted from the package not being properly screened and segregated at the USPS in SAN and LAX.

column168: A WORKER CLOSED THE TANK VALVE ON A TANKER TRAILER TO REMOVE A FILL HOSE FROM THE TANKER LEADING TO A STORAGE TANK IN ORDER TO CLEAN THE HOSE. THE VALVE DID NOT CLOSE FULLY. WHEN THE MATERIAL IN THE TANKER OUTLET VALVE MELTED, MALEIC ANHYDRIDE SPILLED INTO CONTAINMENT AND ONTO CONCRETE PAVEMENT. THE MALEIC ANHYDRIDE RAPIDLY SOLIDIFIED AS IT COOLED TO BELOW 127 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT. NO MATERIAL LEFT THE FACILITY, AND THERE WERE NO ENVIRONMENTAL RISK BEYOND THE IMMEDIATE AREA.
column169: ALL WORKERS WITH RESPONSIBILITY FOR UNLOADING TANKERS WERE RETAINED. SITE WORK INSTRUCTIONS WERE UPDATED TO PROVIDE MORE GUIDANCE ON DEALING WITH UPSET CONDITIONS SUCH AS THOSE THAT EXISTED AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO AVOID ANOTHER ACCIDENT THAT HE CAME UPON. DURING AVOIDANCE VEHICLE ROLLED CAUSING THE TANKER TO PUNCTURE AND RELEASE DIESEL FUEL TO THE SURFACE. FIRST RESPONDERS ARRIVED TO CONTAIN DIESEL FUEL ON SURFACE AND WITHIN TANKER. VA DEM ESTIMATED THAT 5456 GALLONS RELEASED AND WERE NOT RECOVERED DURING THE INITIAL RESPONSE BASED ON MANIFEST AND WHAT WAS RECOVERED FROM THE TANKER. VA DEQ ASSUMED CONTROL OF THE SITE AFTER INITIAL RESPONSE AND HANDLED LONGER TERM CLEANUP OPERATIONS, WHICH CEASED FIRST WEEK OF JULY.
column169: CONTINUED DRIVER TRAINING AND DRIVER DILIGENCE WHEN IT COMES TO OTHER VEHICLE OPERATORS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: COX PETROLEUM TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 14 IN LANE 3 AND AS THE ROAD MADE A SLIGHT RIGHT CURVE THE COX TRANSPORT DRIVER CAME UP ON A MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT THAT OCCURRED EARLIER IN THE MORNING AND HAD LANES 2 & 3 PARTIALLY BLOCKED. COX DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO AVOID CRASH AND THE PEDESTRIANS STANDING IN THE ROAD BY SWERVING TO THE LEFT CAUSING THE TRAILER TO OVERTURN. THE COX DRIVER CALLED 911. THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL, LA COUNTY FIRE AND LA COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED. PATRIOT ENVIRONMENTAL (ACTON, CA) WAS CALLED AS WELL AS PEPE'S TOWING SERVICE. COX PETROLEUM IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED THEIR TERMINAL MANAGER, SAFETY & COMPLIANCE SUPERVISOR, SAFETY & COMPLIANCE MANAGER, MECHANIC, CHIEF OPERATIONS OFFICER. APPROXIMATELY 4400 GALLONS LEAKED FROM THE REAR CARGO TANK TRAILER THAT WAS COMPLETELY UPSIDE DOWN. FUEL APPEARED TO BE SPILLING FROM THE MANWAY COVER FOR APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS. THE FUEL LEAK WAS EVENTUALLY STOPPED BY HAVING THE RESIDUAL FUEL (400 GALLONS) TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER COX TANK TRAILER. PEPE'S TOWING SERVICE UPRIGHTED THE OVERTURNED TRAILER.  GASOLINE FLOWED ALONG THE SHOULDER OF HIGHWAY 14 TO THE SOUTH. A SMALL AMOUNT OF GASOLINE ENTERED THE STORM DRAIN AND INTO A BIO SWELL ALONG THE FREEWAY. PATRIOT WAS INSTRUCTED BY CAL-TRANS TO TENTATIVELY BEGIN REMEDIATION JUNE 1, 2019. THE PROJECT WAS COMPLETED ON JUNE 26TH, 2019.
column169: 1. A "SAFETY ALERT" WILL BE DRAFTED AND SENT OUT TO ALL TERMINALS TO ADDRESS THIS INCIDENT, DEFENSIVE DRIVING AND ROLLOVER PREVENTION.  2. THIS INCIDENT ALONG WITH DEFENSIVE DRIVING & ROLLOVER PREVENTION WILL BE REVIEWED DURING OUR 2ND QUARTER SAFETY MEETINGS STARTING IN JUNE 2019.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: THIS TRUCK WAS TRAVELING ON REDWOOD ROAD IN NAPA, CA TO MAKE A DELIVERY. WHILE TRAVELING WESTBOUND AT A SHARP TURN IN THE ROAD, THE TRUCK ROLLER OVER ON THE PASSENGER SIDE HITTING AND LANDING NEXT TO A ROAD BARRIER. IN THE COURSE OF THE EVENT THE LOAD THAT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED, (COMPRESSED GAS CYLINDERS STRAPPED TO METAL PALLETS) BECAME SEPARATED FROM THE TRUCK, THE PASSENGER SIDE PALLETS STAYED ON THE GROUND, THE DRIVER SIDE PALLETS SEPARATED FROM THE TRAILER AND DEPOSITED ON TOP OF THE BOTTOM PALLETS AND ON THE GROUND ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE ROAD BARRIER. LIQUID ARGON AND LIQUID NITROGEN CONTAINERS BECAME TURNED UPSIDE DOWN. THE ACCIDENT SCENE WAS SECURED BY POLICE, FIRE, LOCAL HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDERS AND THE COMPLETE WELDERS SUPPLY RESPONSE TEAM. THE CYLINDERS WERE STABILIZED, TURNED UPRIGHT AND REMOVED FORM THE ACCIDENT SCENE. THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS PUT UPRIGHT AND THEN TOWED TO THE REPAIR SHOP. THE DRIVER WAS EVALUATED AT THE SCENE AND CLEARED BY LOCAL POLICE. THE INCIDENT IN TOTAL ESTIMATED AROUND 7 HOURS. THE RELEASE ESTIMATED 3 HOURS.
column169: THE ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION RESULTED IN REITERATING SAFETY PROTOCOLS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. SAFETY BRIEFINGS AND MEETINGS. THOROUGH PRE-TRIP/POST-TRIP INSPECTIONS ARE TO BE FOLLOWED FOR ALL CMV'S BEFORE EVERY TRIP. ALL SPEED LIMITS ARE TO BE STRICTLY FOLLOWED AND CONTINUAL MONITORING WITH OUR GPS SYSTEM. DAILY & WEEKLY DRIVERS SAFETY SCORECARDS COLLECTED WITH GPS DATA TO INFORM MANAGEMENT ON DRIVERS DRIVING, DRIVING BEHAVIOR/HABITS. ADDED ADDITIONAL OVERSIGHT TO ENSURE ALL D.O.T. RULES AND REGULATIONS ARE BEING FOLLOWED. ALL LOADS TO BE FULLY SECURED AND FREQUENT STRAP CHECKS ARE TO BE MADE DURING THE COURSE OF THE WORKDAY TO ENSURE SECURITY.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: ON MAY 28, 2019 A CONTRACT CARRIER POWER UNIT PULLING A MESSER NON-SPECIFICATION CRYOGENIC TRAILER STOPPED AT A CUSTOMER SITE (IN BAYAMON, PUERTO RICO) TO MAKE A NITROGEN DELIVERY. THE DRIVER NOTICED ICE BUILD-UP ON THE BACK OF THE PUMP. HE PROCEEDED TO POUR WATER OVER THE ICE TO MELT IT AND IDENTIFY THE ISSUE, BUT THE ICE AND NITROGEN RELEASE INCREASED. THE CONTRACT DRIVER CONTACTED THE MESSER TRANSPORT SUPERVISOR TO NOTIFY OF THE INCIDENT WHO THEN SENT A MESSER DRIVER AND CUSTOMER SERVICE TECHNICIAN TO THE SCENE TO HELP WITH THE ISSUE.  WHEN THE SERVICE TECHNICIAN AND SECOND DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMER, THE LEAK HAD INCREASED IN VOLUME. THE MESSER EMERGENCY MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED. IT WAS AGREED TO LET APPROXIMATELY 2000 GALLONS OF NITROGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID (LIN) VENT AND THEN REPAIR THE LEAK. THE TRAILER'S SAMPLE LINE HAD RUPTURED AT APPROXIMATELY 1/4" FROM WHERE THE LINE WENT THROUGH THE REAR SHELL OF THE OUTER VESSEL. AS A RESULT, THE COLD LIN HAD CAUSED MOISTURE IN THE AIR TO SOLIDIFY AND FORM AROUND THE POINT OF THE LEAK.  EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DID NOT RESPOND BUT NOTIFIED PR ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY BOARD. THE PR EQB WENT OUTSIDE TO CHECK HOW THE RESPONSE WAS GOING AND REQUESTED THAT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER BE NOTIFIED. THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED; INCIDENT NUMBER 1247061.
column169: FIRE DEPARTMENT AND BAYAMON COUNTY EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AT 1:45PM. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED TO HELP WITH THE RESPONSE. CUSTOMER PREMISES WERE MONITORED FOR %O2 AS PRECAUTIONARY METHOD AS THE COLD LIN WAS CAUSING A LIQUID VAPOR CLOUD TO FORM. ALL LEVELS WERE FOUND BETWEEN 20-21%. NRC WAS NOTIFIED @ 15:45 AS A COURTESY CALL AS REQUESTED BY PR-EQB SINCE N2 DOES NOT HAVE A RQ. ENFORCEMENT OFFICIALS ASSISTED IN ESCORTING THE TRAILER TO THE MESSER CATANO SITE. THE SAMPLE LINE WAS THEN REPAIRED.

column168: The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

During loading, the loading rack put hoses in from the top using wire to hold them up.  One of the hoses came off and spilled approximately 25 gallons of Sodium Hydroxide Solution around the dome lid and the side of trailer. The product spilled onto the ground (dirt/gravel).  There is no containment area at this rack.  The rack is cleaning up. The trailer has been cleaned, and on site personnel are cleaning up the spill with lime to neutralize the product.
column169: This was a loading rack issue with their system that called the spill.  They are going to redesign the system so that it won't happen again.
